'''Colin Strang, 2nd Baron Strang''' (12 June 1922 – 19 December 2014) was a [[United Kingdom|British]] Professor of [[Philosophy]] and [[hereditary peer]].

== Life ==
Strang was the only son of [[William Strang, 1st Baron Strang]], a diplomat who served as [[Permanent Under-Secretary at the Foreign Office]]<ref name=":0">{{Cite book|url=https://doi.org/10.1093/ref:odnb/69691|title=Strang [née Carr], Barbara Mary Hope, Lady Strang (1925–1982), English language scholar|last=Haigh|first=John D.|date=2004-09-23|publisher=Oxford University Press|series=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography|language=en|doi=10.1093/ref:odnb/69691}}</ref> from 1949 to 1953, and was subsequently the first [[Crossbencher#|Convenor of the Crossbench peers]] in the [[House of Lords]] from 1968 to 1974.

Strang was a Lecturer in Philosophy at [[Queens University, Belfast]] from 1951 to 1953 and at [[King's College, Newcastle]] from 1953 to 1975. He was Professor of Philosophy at [[Newcastle University|University of Newcastle]] from 1975 to 1982 and Dean of Faculty of Arts at University of Newcastle from 1976 to 1979.<ref name=peerage/>

He succeeded to the title in 1978. He married the English scholar [[Barbara Strang]] and they had one daughter.<ref name=peerage>{{cite web|url=http://www.cracroftspeerage.co.uk/online/content/strang1954.htm|title=Strang, Baron (UK, 1954)|publisher=cracroftspeerage.co.uk|date=21 Aug 2004}}</ref><ref name=":0" /> He married again twice. The peerage became extinct on his death in 2014.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://peeragenews.blogspot.co.uk/2015/01/2nd-baron-strang-1922-2014.html|title=2nd Baron Strang 1922-2014|publisher=Peerage News|date=3 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theguardian.com/education/2015/jan/20/colin-strang|title=Colin Strang obituary|last=Charlton|first=William|date=2015-01-20|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-09-14}}</ref>

