{{refimprove|date=October 2008}}
The '''NIA''' Technique is a mind/body physical conditioning program that initially stood for Non-Impact Aerobics, a health and fitness alternative that emerged in the '80's, and evolved to include neurological integrative practices and teachings.<ref>[http://www.vitalitylink.com/modality-NIA-previously-Non-Impact-Aerobics,-Neuromuscular-Integrative-Action-353 Vitality Link.com, "Neuromuscular Integrative Action"]</ref><ref>[http://www.healersworldwide.com/article/what-is-nia-neuromuscular-integrative-action/ Healers Worldwide, "What is NIA"]</ref>  The Nia Technique was founded in 1983 by Debbie Rosas and Carlos AyaRosas in the San Francisco area. Nia combines martial arts, modern dance arts and yoga in a workout set to music.<ref>[http://www.inwardboundadventures.com/nia.html Inward Bound Adventures, "What is NIA?"]</ref>

== History ==
From 1972 to 1983 Debbie Rosas operated an exercise business in the San Francisco Bay Area known as the Bod Squad.<ref>[https://books.google.es/books?id=KGEEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA77&lpg=PA77&dq=Debbie+Rosas+Bod+Squad&source=bl&ots=R9jlYs4YQE&sig=J11rgo3t2m_7Wir_WDXHVclgMhU&hl=en&sa=X&ei=hgPNVIawA4mtU6eegqgO&ved=0CDYQ6AEwBA#v=onepage&q=Debbie%20Rosas%20Bod%20Squad&f=false Working Mother Magazine, Nov 1986, "Low-Impact Aerobics"]</ref>  In 1983 a series of sports related injuries prompted her to research and develop an alternative method of [[aerobic exercise]] and [[strength training]] aiming for safe, non-impact, [[bodymind]] based movement.

This led to the establishment of the Nia Technique.<ref>[http://www.nexuspub.com/articles_2006/interview_nia_06_jf.php Nexus Colorado Interview Jan/Feb 2006 "A Moving Story: Interview with Carlos Rosas and Debbie Rosas"]</ref> Nia Technique headquarters moved to Portland, Oregon in 1991 and is currently overseen by Debbie Rosas, CEO.

== Nia Technique ==
Nia dance cardio fitness classes are taught by instructors licensed in the  Nia Technique.  Each class includes mindful movement guidance and [[Somatosensory system|somatic]] education; class cycles include warm-up, sustained non-impact aerobic conditioning, [[strength training]], cool down and stretching.  Nia Fitness classes are taught to music, including [[Pop music|pop]], [[electronica]], [[jazz]], [[Latin music (genre)|Latin]], [[New Age]], [[Indian music|Indian]] and [[hip hop]]. They employ 52 basic movements and techniques that draw on a combination of Jazz, Modern and [[Duncan Dance]] styles, [[Tai Chi]], [[TaeKwonDo]] and [[Aikido]]; and the [[bodymind]] [[healing arts]] of [[Feldenkrais Method]], [[Alexander Technique]] and [[Yoga]].

